            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" resp="#AL">
                <div type="textpart" subtype="section" n="A" xml:lang="grc">
                    <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>οἱ <roleName type="civic" subtype="decurio">δεκορίωνες</roleName>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested"><name type="praenomen"><expan><abbr>Μ</abbr><ex>άρκον</ex></expan></name> <name type="nomen">Οὐαλέριον</name> <persName type="attested"><name type="patronymic">Διογνήτου</name>
                    <lb n="3"/><name type="patronymic">Μῆγα</name></persName> <w>υἱὸν</w> <name type="cognomen">Χόρτωνα</name></persName>                    
                    <lb n="4"/><roleName type="paracivic" subtype="euergetes">εὐεργέταν</roleName>
                </ab>
                </div>
                <div type="textpart" subtype="section" n="B" xml:lang="la">
                    <ab>
                        <lb n="1"/>ordo et populus <expan><abbr>civit</abbr><ex>atis</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>Lilybit</abbr><ex>anorum</ex></expan> 
                        <lb n="2"/><roleName type="paracivic" subtype="patron">patrono</roleName> perpetuo
                    </ab>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>text according to IG</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p><!--translation(s) - add @xml:lang for 'en' or 'it' to div--></p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--to Marcus Valerius Chorton (son of Diognetos Megas), for his euergetism, by the Lilybaetanians, i.e. 'hoi Dekoriones M. Oualerion Diognetou Mega huion Chortana euergetan'; CIL 10.7240 is on the reverse of the stone - not a direct transl., but much the same thing viz. 'ordo et populus civit. Lilybit patrono perpetuo'. ordo et populus is transl. of boule kai demos; cf. IG 14.273 (also IG 14.575, from Centuripe). SEG 34.951 is another inscription containing the father of this man, which implies that this is not later than Augustan, since that is, so M-P, poss. C2 BC. SEG 37 is an observation simply that Megas is a name, not a tribal. Robert and Mason note that this inscription currently seems to be the unique example of the Greek transcr. of decurio in the sense of 'bouleutes'. cf. SEG.37.1814 andBE 1961.119--></p>
            </div>
